Rize Airport will be built on the sea
Rize Airport will be the second airport to be built in Turkey with sea fill.
Rize Airport will be built on a 266-hectare area between the village of Yeşilköy and the location of Kız Kulesi in Pazar district, on a sea wall 26 to 32 meters from the coast.
Due to the depth of the Rize airport, about three times more filling material will be used than at the Ardu-Giresun Airport.
The project will build a runway 45 meters wide and 3,000 meters long with a apron that can accommodate 36 planes per hour.
Rize Airport, which will generally serve passenger and cargo aircraft, is also expected to serve aircraft with a class D composition, turbulence class heavy, takeoff weight of more than 150 thousand kilograms.
Rize Airport project, which will be tendered by the General Directorate of Infrastructure Investments of the Ministry of Transport, Maritime Affairs and Communications on September 8, will be built in the first phase with sea filling, runway, apron, taxiway, bypass, safety wire mesh, fences, PAT fields and environmental lighting.
These works will cost 600 million lire.
After the infrastructure works, the upper structure will be built, including the terminal buildings, with a cost of 150 million liras.
Rize Airport will be completed in two years and nine months.
