Watch out for this habit in kids
Dr. Bilgin Giray, of the Faculty of Dentistry, said that since children are unable to chew at an early age, they relax with this reflex by making sucking a necessity.
Dr. Giray, who lists the reasons for the habit of sucking fingers in children, says: "Finger sucking is a phenomenon that occurs from birth to 3-4 years of age".
Most babies suck their thumbs.
The child sucks his thumb to satisfy his need for suckling as a baby, and after 1 and a half years, he sucks his thumb to satisfy and relax his craving for his mother's breast.
"He can be bored and distracted, and he can be finger-sucking when he's sleepy, when he's nervous, when he's away from his mother", she said.
Doç, who emphasized that the reason for the behavior of sucking fingers in old age is the lack of parent-child relationship and lack of confidence in the child, Dr. Bilgin Giray explained the effects of this behavior on dental health:
The sucking behavior of the fingers has a negative effect on the formation of the child's dental structure.
The pressure exerted during suction pushes the upper teeth forward, while the lower teeth push back.
This causes the lower jaw to recede, disrupting the balance of the palate and the tooth structure.
And the physiological implication is speech disorder and aesthetically unpleasant closure.
Dr. Doç Giray, who points out that if no early solution is found, a much more complex treatment process can occur in the 6-7 years of age when permanent teeth begin to emerge, "We can protect our children from closure and joint problems before the jaw development is complete".
"So today, children need to be controlled in their oral structure, just like they need to be controlled in their eyes and ears", he concluded.
