You can't use a varicose vein in a heart surgery!
Varicose veins are a disease that has been increasing in frequency in recent years.
In the case of the hereditary factor of genetic proximity, long working hours, long standing and sitting jobs lead to an increase in hereditary complaints.
Do you use veins in heart surgery?
I have a hernia, and people often ask me, "What if I have a heart attack?"
Here are the answers to those questions.
There are two types of collecting system in the leg:
First, there's a deep venous system in the leg called the main artery, which carries the dirty blood to the lungs and collects the dirty blood from the main leg.
These are called the deep femoral vein and the superficial femoral vein.
Problems with these arteries are less common, and when they are diseased, the vessels cannot be closed, and medications are used to keep them open.
In the leg, there's a superficial venous system called the lateral pathway, which carries dirty blood to the lungs and then connects to the deep venous system in the pelvis.
This system consists of two large and two small collective veins called safenas.
In all four of these veins, there may be a failure and a hernia.
The coronary arteries used in heart surgery are superficial coronary arteries called large safen veins.
The absence of these vessels is not harmful to the body and therefore can be used in heart surgery.
But for these vessels to be used in heart surgery, they have to be healthy.
Because the heart is a very important organ.
The surgical removal of the varicose veins or the laser burn that leaves them in place also reduces the workload on the deep veins and makes the leg healthier.
There's a common misconception that veins, even hereditary, can be used as a backup.
A varicose vein is never and never used in heart surgery!
There are other veins that can be used in heart surgery.
The backup vascular systems that can be used in heart surgery are located under the chest wall, around the stomach, and in the arm.
