NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
According to NASA's new climate model, Venus once had habitable conditions.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model to explore the past of Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus once hosted conditions similar to Earth, with its hot, waterless surface and CO2-filled atmosphere.
Scientists have previously attributed Venus' slow rotation to its thick atmosphere.
But the latest estimates suggest that Venus may have had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere and could still rotate slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of ancient Venus.
Although there are more dry regions of the planet than Earth, it may have once had sufficient water and protection from rapid evaporation by geographical variability.
Ancient Venus also benefited from a sun that was 30 percent fainter.
"The GISS model simulates a slow rotation of Venus that causes the sun to face the day side for almost two months at a time", said GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio in a news release.
This heated the surface, creating rain that formed thick cloud layers that moved like an umbrella to protect the surface from solar heat.
As a result, the average climate temperatures were only a few degrees colder than Earth is today.
The model allowed for Venus to form a story similar to the evolution that planetary scientists had previously hypothesized.
Although once habitable, Venus has been subjected to a great deal of heat and ultraviolet light over the course of billions of years.
Their oceans evaporated and the water vapor burned away in the ultraviolet rays.
The hydrogen ran out, leaving behind only a thick atmosphere filled with deadly greenhouse gases, carbon dioxide, which is what we know today as Venus.
The researchers shared the results of their new Venus climate model in the Journal of Geophysical Research.
