The Kepler space telescope, with its latest mission, has helped astronomers create the most complete catalogue of the rotation speeds of stars in the constellation Ursa Major.
The new data help astronomers understand why stars in the constellation rotate at varying speeds and how rotation periods are related to planet formation.
Luisa Rebull, a research scientist at Caltech's Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis in Pasadena, said in a news release: "By comparing our results to star clusters, we hope to learn more about the relationship between a star's mass, age, and even the history of the solar system".
The star of the constellation Ulker is 445 light-years from Earth.
Most of the stars in the cluster formed 125 million years ago and are reaching new levels of maturity.
They're spinning at the fastest speed they've ever seen in their lives.
At peak rotation rates, stars in this maturing stage generate a large amount of stellar wind.
These winds cause refraction on the stars as they move through the stars' magnetic fields.
As a star ages, its rotation rate decreases.
Kepler measures the rotation speed of each star by tracking the time between appearances of noticeable star spots, such as sunspots.
The latest rotation velocity catalogue suggests that larger stars rotate faster than smaller ones.
Rebull compared the stars to dancers, stating that the larger ones perform their turn on one foot more slowly than the smaller ones.
Rebull says, "We see that in the Ulker 'ballet' the slow ones are much heavier, and the fast ones are very light stars".
Because the Ulker team is so close to its star, it serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory for comparing rotation speeds with stellar properties.
Rebull said, "The Ulker team provides theoretical models for star rotations in both directions, as young and old as the star".
There's more we want to know about how, when and why the stars' rotation rates fall, why they leave their dancing shoes in a corner, so to speak.
Rebull and colleagues have detailed their latest analysis of the rotation speeds of the Ulker star cluster in three new papers to be published soon in the Journal of Astronomy.
